post_text:
We have emailed parents and guardians important information about completing Back to School Gateway forms for each student. If you have multiple students, you will need to complete the Back to School Gateway forms for each student. Back to School Gateway replaces the beginning of year forms that are normally completed on paper. You do not need to complete Back to School Gateway if your student is newly enrolled in the district for the 2020-21 school year. The deadline to complete Back to School Gateway is Friday, October 16 at 4 p.m. Failure to do so could result in your student losing technology access.

If you did not receive the email, information about contacting your student‚Äôs building is on our website. https://www.huberheightscityschools.org/News/back-to-school-gateway-information

Parent and student information sessions for Schools PLP will be held on Wednesday (8/26) & Thursday (8/27) from 6:30 - 7:30 pm. These meetings will be hosted by Matt Housh, HHCS Director of Curriculum & Instruction, and Stacie Anderson-Cook, Curriculum Supervisor for the Montgomery County ESC. We want to provide information about Schools PLP, our online coursework program, and demonstrate how students and parents can access this dynamic system. The meetings will take place using YouTube streaming so we can accommodate lots of participants. We look forward to helping you get this year started on the right foot!

8/26 YouTube streaming link: https://youtu.be/d9xB3PbSAqM
8/27 YouTube streaming link: https://youtu.be/Tb255gfm3Gc

post_text: Starting July 1, registration for all new students in grades preschool through high school will be completed online using Registration Gateway through the HHCS website. Parents/guardians of existing HHCS students will also have the ability to complete their student's back to school paperwork online through Back to School Gateway. Families that complete the Adult Residency Affidavits will have the ability to upload the completed Affidavit and supporting documents through Back to School Gateway. Visit https://www.huberheightscityschools.org/Content/registration for more registration information and forms.

Just got off of the phone with the Montgomery County Health Department. We have some great news to announce here for the first time:

As of today, our marching band can practice using the same guidelines as are being used for sports teams! This would also apply to the Warriorettes.

Our graduation hopes of a formal ceremony on July 12 is still up in the air. Guidance permitting these large gatherings has not been released yet.

This is great news for those hoping to get started with band practice this summer.

Go Warriors!

Mario Basora

post_text: Students who are taking Advanced Placement classes and planning to take the AP exam this spring can take the 45-minute online exam at home. They will be able to take these exams on any device including computers, tablets or smartphones. Taking a photo of handwritten work will also be an option. The exam questions are designed to prevent cheating. AP will use a range of digital security tools and techniques ‚Äì including plagiarism detection software ‚Äì to protect the integrity of the exams. Beginning on Wednesday, March 25, students and schools will have access to free, live AP review lessons delivered by AP teachers from across the country. The lessons will focus on reviewing skills and concepts from the first 75% of the course. These mobile-friendly classes are designed to be used alongside work that may be given by schools and will be available on-demand so teachers and students can access them at any time. The specific test dates and free-response question types will be posted by April 3 at AP Central. There will be two different testing dates.

post_text:
Dear Huber Heights families,

We are in the middle of an exciting hiring process for our next Wayne High School Principal. As an essential part of our process, the three finalists will each be asked to give a personal presentation to parents and community members, followed by a structured question and answer time. At the end of the presentation and Q&A time, you will have a chance to give feedback for each candidate. The candidate forums are scheduled from 4:30 - 5:30 p.m. on March 10, 11, and 12, 2020 in the Wayne High School library. Each evening will feature a different finalist. We encourage you to attend all three nights.

The forums will be the final part of a long process for each candidate, who in addition to going through two interviews on separate dates, will have spent the entire day at Wayne interacting/interviewing with students and staff.

This will be a great opportunity to participate in the process of hiring the next principal at Wayne High School. We hope you can make it.

Go Warriors!

Mario Basora, Superintendent

As an essential part of our process, the three finalists will each be asked to give a personal presentation to parents and community members, followed by a structured question and answer time. At the end of the presentation and Q&A time, you will have a chance to give feedback for each candidate. The candidate forums are scheduled from 4:30 - 5:30 p.m. on March 10, 11, and 12, 2020 in the Wayne High School library. Each evening will feature a different finalist. We encourage you to attend all three nights.

The forums will be the final part of a long process for each candidate, who in addition to going through two interviews on separate dates, will have spent the entire day at Wayne interacting/interviewing with students and staff.

This will be a great opportunity to participate in the process of hiring the next principal at Wayne High School. We hope you can make it.

Go Warriors!

Mario Basora, Superintendent
